    "title": {
        "rendered": "Cover Me: Seven Nights to Rock"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "<p>Aubrey &#8220;Moon&#8221; Mullican was never the crossover star he should have been.</p>\n<p>Born in 1909, Mullican was too old to ride the rock and roll wave when it crested, even though he helped create it.</p>\n<p>Known as the &#8220;King of the Hillbilly Piano Players&#8221; (which is much more of a compliment than it might sound), Mullican nevertheless scored a series of Top Ten country hits, starting with &#8220;<a href=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2019/08/29/matr-gary-u-s-bonds-and-bruce-springsteen-jole-blon/\">Jole Blon</a>&#8221; in 1947 when he was already thirty-eight.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/N9c5Fz5PMLQ?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>In 1951, his music took a turn toward what would eventually become rock and roll with the release of one of his biggest hits, &#8220;Cherokee Boogie.&#8221;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/9jJCd2gOgjk?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>As we can hear, Mullican was a\u00a0 pretty mean pianist, and &#8220;Cherokee Boogie&#8221; and his subsequent work influenced the much younger Jerry Lee Lewis, who took Mullican&#8217;s sound and ran with it.</p>\n<p>By the time Mullican released &#8220;Seven Nights to Rock&#8221;\u00a0 in 1956, he was approaching fifty and eclipsed by Lewis, Chuck Berry, and other early rockers.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/R00dWeHB28U?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;Seven Nights to Rock&#8221; should have been a hit. It&#8217;s reminiscent of iconic songs like &#8220;Rock Around the Clock&#8221; and other songs that lit up the charts, yet it never charted for Mullican. It&#8217;s hard not to conclude that his age had something to do with it: rock was music for the young, and it must have seemed at least a little odd to hear the elder Mullican sing of &#8220;rocking&#8221; with a different girl every night of the week.</p>\n<p>That didn&#8217;t stop a score of artists from covering it in later years though. Notable versions included Nick Lowe&#8217;s cover in 1985 and a 2012 rendition by The Connection that was anointed &#8220;Coolest Song in the World&#8221; by Little Steven.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/TDriok3B38A?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Bruce Springsteen covered it, too&#8211;more than one hundred times, in fact. It was a staple throughout the back half of the Rising Tour, where it often immediately followed &#8220;Born to Run,&#8221; benefiting from the adrenaline rush that led into it.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZL71sM11w2I?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Bruce played &#8220;Seven Nights to Rock&#8221; several times on the Magic, Working on a Dream, Wrecking Ball, and River Tours, too, although it never again sounded as vital as it did on the Rising Tour.</p>\n<p>There was one particularly memorable performance in 2014, though, when Patti Scialfa decided that perhaps seven nights was a bit\u00a0<em>too </em>much rocking for her husband, and that perhaps <em>she</em> might like to do a bit of rocking, too&#8230;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='758' height='427' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/4YwZBIDDpck?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span></div>\n<p>&#8220;Seven Nights to Rock&#8221; hasn&#8217;t exactly been a staple of Bruce&#8217;s set lists since the Rising Tour, but it&#8217;s never really been gone either. In fact, Bruce has played it at least once almost every year since the Rising Tour (including non-touring years) and as recently as late 2019 at The Stone Pony.</p>\n<p>So odds are good that as soon as we&#8217;re fortunate enough for\u00a0<em>any\u00a0</em>night to rock, &#8220;Seven Nights to Rock&#8221; will be a wild card candidate in Bruce&#8217;s set lists.</p>\n<p><strong>Seven Nights to Rock<br />\nFirst performed:</strong> April 13, 2002 (Asbury Park, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> November 16, 2019 (Asbury Park, NJ)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
    "excerpt": {
        "rendered": "<p>On the Rising Tour (and pretty much every year since) Bruce resurrected an obscure single from one of rock&#8217;s great but forgotten influencers.</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
